      <description>&lt;p&gt;After a 9-hour introductory class to Blender, I took on the challenge of creating a 3D model of my Taylor 510ce guitar. In this article, I&amp;rsquo;ll walk you through the steps I followed to bring this project to life.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/posts/cg/blender-project/taylor_guitar.png&#34; alt=&#34;Rendered image&#34;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&#34;gathering-reference-image&#34;&gt;Gathering Reference image&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To start, I began by capturing reference photos of my guitar from both side and front angles.
&lt;div class=&#34;row&#34;&gt;
    
       &lt;div class=&#34;col col-sm-12 col-lg-6&#34;&gt;
            &lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/posts/cg/blender-project/face_guitar.png&#34; alt=&#34;face&#34; height=&#34;500&#34;&gt;

        &lt;/div&gt;
    
       &lt;div class=&#34;col col-sm-12 col-lg-6&#34;&gt;
            &lt;img src=&#34;http://localhost:1313/posts/cg/blender-project/side_guitar.png&#34; alt=&#34;side&#34; height=&#34;500&#34;&gt;

        &lt;/div&gt;
    
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I then removed the background of these images using Photoshop and put them as background images on x and y axis in Blender.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
